<figureCitation box="[353,430,1134,1158]" captionStart="Figs 52–55" captionStartId="21.[113,150,1511,1530]" captionTargetBox="[170,1033,222,1469]" captionTargetId="figure-14@21.[163,1040,218,1474]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="Figs 52–55. Habitus. 52 – Hesperopenna bonifaci sp. nov. (male, holotype, 9.5 mm); 53 – H. helferi sp. nov. (male, paratype, 8.5 mm); 54 – H. sipekorum sp. nov. (male, holotype, 8.6 mm); 55 – H. zofka sp. nov. (male, holotype, 6.9 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740065" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740065/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="739">Fig. 55</figureCitation>
). Body yellowish orange, apices of mandibles black, antennomeres I and II yellowish, rest of antennomeres black, extreme lateral margin of epipleura in basal half black. Femora yellowish, tibiae and tarsi black, last two tarsomeres and claws dark brown. Last ventrite posteriorly with two small incisions (
<figureCitation box="[689,769,1230,1254]" captionStart="Figs 19–26" captionStartId="15.[112,149,1058,1077]" captionTargetBox="[124,1078,218,1029]" captionTargetId="figure-153@15.[113,1088,207,1034]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="Figs 19–26. Last abdominal ventrite of males.19 – Hesperopenna medvedevi nom. nov.; 20 – H. persimilis (Kimoto, 1989); 21 – H. tibialis (Kimoto, 1989); 22 – H. arnoldi sp. nov.; 23 – H. bonifaci sp. nov.; 24 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 25 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 26 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740049" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740049/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="739">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1128,818,1574]" pageId="24" pageNumber="739">Interocular space 1.5 times as wide as transverse diameter of eye. Antennae 0.9 times as long as body, length ratio of antennomeres I to XI equals 15-5-7-14-14-15-15-15-15-13-15. Pronotum 1.40 times as broad as long. Elytra glabrous, 1.75 times as long as wide (measured at humeral calli), 0.75 times as long as body. Length ratio of metatarsomeres I–IV equals 12-6-4-9.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1128,818,1574]" pageId="24" pageNumber="739">
Aedeagus: dorsal side apically with symmetrical triangular incision; ventral side with very long thin incision medially (
<figureCitation box="[453,531,1454,1478]" captionStart="Figs 15–18" captionStartId="13.[115,152,1542,1561]" captionTargetBox="[126,1079,226,1362]" captionTargetId="figure-14@13.[113,1090,218,1370]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 15–18. Aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view; c – ventral view). 15 – H. bonifaci sp. nov.; 16 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 17 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 18 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740045/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="739">Fig. 18</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="24.[151,1128,818,1574]" pageId="24" pageNumber="739">
Female. Last ventrite with wide concavity at apex, lateral sides slightly concave (
<figureCitation box="[1036,1113,1486,1510]" captionStart="Figs 27–33" captionStartId="17.[113,149,1518,1537]" captionTargetBox="[138,1066,210,1470]" captionTargetId="figure-14@17.[135,1067,206,1474]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="Figs 27–33.Last abdominal ventrite of females. 27 – Hesperopenna medvedevi nom.nov.; 28 – H.persimilis (Kimoto, 1989); 29 – H. tibialis (Kimoto, 1989); 30 – H. arnoldi sp. nov.; 31 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 32 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 33 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740051" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740051/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="739">Fig. 33</figureCitation>
), pygidium with simple sharp triangular tip (
<figureCitation box="[618,700,1518,1542]" captionStart="Figs 34–40" captionStartId="18.[151,188,1519,1538]" captionTargetBox="[231,1053,221,1476]" captionTargetId="figure-10@18.[218,1059,210,1480]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs 34–40. Female pygidium. 34 – Hesperopenna medvedevi nom. nov.; 35 – H. persimilis (Kimoto, 1989); 36 – H. tibialis (Kimoto, 1989); 37 – H. arnoldi sp. nov.; 38 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 39 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 40 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740055/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="739">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
). Spermatheca: nodulus large, globular, cornu regularly rounded, slightly narrower than nodulus (
<figureCitation box="[763,843,1550,1574]" captionStart="Figs 41–47" captionStartId="19.[112,149,1518,1537]" captionTargetBox="[208,996,760,1504]" captionTargetId="figure-215@19.[204,1000,749,1508]" captionTargetPageId="19" captionText="Figs 41–47. Spermatheca. 41 – Hesperopenna medvedevi nom. nov.; 42 – H. persimilis (Kimoto, 1989); 43 – H. tibialis (Kimoto, 1989); 44 – H. arnoldi sp. nov.; 45 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 46 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 47 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 0.25 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740059" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740059/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="739">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="25.[113,1089,219,660]" box="[144,893,219,243]" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">Variability. Ratio width/length of pronotum varies between 1.40–1.55.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="740" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="25.[113,1089,219,660]" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,359,251,275]" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2013" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2013" box="[363,576,253,276]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Hesperopenna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zofka" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[363,576,253,276]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">Hesperopenna zofka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[581,661,252,275]" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kimoto" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[842,945,253,276]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Liroetiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tibialis">
<emphasis box="[842,945,253,276]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">H. tibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Both species share a similar structure of aedeagus with a very long basal orifice longer than the proximal part of aedeagus, bicolorous legs and glabrous elytra. 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2013" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2013" box="[664,877,317,340]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Hesperopenna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zofka" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[664,877,317,340]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">Hesperopenna zofka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[881,961,316,339]" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kimoto" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[113,218,349,372]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Liroetiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tibialis">
<emphasis box="[113,218,349,372]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">H. tibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in black antennae with first two antennomeres yellow (completely yellow antennae in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kimoto" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[143,251,381,404]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Liroetiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tibialis">
<emphasis box="[143,251,381,404]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">H. tibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and in epipleura always with black extreme lateral margin in the basal half (epipleura completely yellow or at most with brownish extreme lateral margin in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kimoto" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[967,1073,413,436]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Liroetiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tibialis">
<emphasis box="[967,1073,413,436]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">H. tibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Males can be distinguished by the long thin incision on the ventral side of aedeagus which is placed medially in 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2013" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2013" box="[314,401,477,500]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Hesperopenna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zofka" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[314,401,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">H. zofka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[407,489,476,499]" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
while placed on the right side in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kimoto" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[836,941,477,500]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Liroetiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tibialis">
<emphasis box="[836,941,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">H. tibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[954,1036,475,500]" captionStart="Figs 11–14" captionStartId="12.[151,188,1557,1576]" captionTargetBox="[158,1115,231,1431]" captionTargetId="figure-10@12.[151,1126,219,1436]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Figs 11–14.Aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view; c – ventral view). 11 – Hesperopenna medvedevi nom.nov.; 12 – H. persimilis (Kimoto, 1989); 13 – H. tibialis (Kimoto, 1989); 14 – H. arnoldi sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740043" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740043/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">Figs 13</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1046,1075,476,500]" captionStart="Figs 15–18" captionStartId="13.[115,152,1542,1561]" captionTargetBox="[126,1079,226,1362]" captionTargetId="figure-14@13.[113,1090,218,1370]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="Figs 15–18. Aedeagus (a – dorsal view; b – lateral view; c – ventral view). 15 – H. bonifaci sp. nov.; 16 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 17 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 18 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740045" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740045/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">18</figureCitation>
). Females of both species can be separated by the shape of pygidium: apex simply triangular in 
<taxonomicName authority="Bezděk, 2013" authorityName="Bezděk" authorityYear="2013" box="[141,229,541,564]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Hesperopenna" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zofka" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[141,229,541,564]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">H. zofka</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[236,319,540,563]" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
while distinctly pointed in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Kimoto" baseAuthorityYear="1989" box="[611,717,541,564]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Liroetiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="25" pageNumber="740" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tibialis">
<emphasis box="[611,717,541,564]" italics="true" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">H. tibialis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[732,857,539,564]" captionStart="Figs 34–40" captionStartId="18.[151,188,1519,1538]" captionTargetBox="[231,1053,221,1476]" captionTargetId="figure-10@18.[218,1059,210,1480]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="Figs 34–40. Female pygidium. 34 – Hesperopenna medvedevi nom. nov.; 35 – H. persimilis (Kimoto, 1989); 36 – H. tibialis (Kimoto, 1989); 37 – H. arnoldi sp. nov.; 38 – H. helferi sp. nov.; 39 – H. sipekorum sp. nov.; 40 – H. zofka sp. nov. Scale bar 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740055" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740055/files/figure.png" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">Figs 36, 40</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="25" pageNumber="740" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="25.[113,1089,219,660]" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,242,572,596]" pageId="25" pageNumber="740">Etymology.</emphasis>
Dedicated to Žofka the small black cat of Jiří Hájek and Květa Kalíková. Noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
